      <div xml:id="NA270-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu (ET: parattaiyar palarōṭum oḻukutal kāṇappoṟāta kātal parattai vāyiṉ maṟuppa avaḷ) tōḻi nērkkiṉṟāḷ talaimakaṉai neruṅkic colli vāyil etirkoṇṭatu. [uṭaṉilaik kiḷavivakaiyāl.]</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante as one who agrees receives a mediator, speaking directed to HIM.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA270">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            taṭantāṭ ṭāḻaik kuṭampai nōṉāt</l>
<l>            taṇṭalai kamaḻum vaṇṭupaṭu nāṟṟat</l>
<l>            tiruḷpurai kūntaṟ poṅkutuka ḷāṭi</l>
<l>            yuruḷpoli pōla vemmuṉai varunta</l>
<l>            laṇittakai yallatu piṇitta ṟēṟṟāp </l>
<l>            peruntōṭ celvat tivaḷiṉu mellā</l>
<l>            veṟperi taḷittaṉai nīyē poṟpuṭai</l>
<l>            viriyuḷaip polinta pariyuṭai naṉmāṉ</l>
<l>            vēnta rōṭṭiya vēntuvē ṉaṉṉaṉ</l>
<l>            kūntaṉ muraṟciyiṟ koṭitē </l>
<l>            maṟappaṉ mātōniṉ viṟaṟṟakai maiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O friend,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ellā</term> is one of these words occurring only as vocatives, and it is used as an address towards a friend, according to T.V.G. male as well as female. Here it seems to be directed to HIM, and my suggestion is to ignore the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> and read the poem as a triangle poem (as they are occasionally found but always denied by tradition), that is, the man seems to have become involved with two women that are close to each other.</note> you cared more for me</l>
<l rend="indent2">than for her with the richness of big shoulders,</l>
<l rend="indent2">who did not make clear [to me her] fettering [you],</l>
<l rend="indent">apart from [her] being fit to be adorned,</l>
<l rend="indent">[and her] suffering in front of us, as a grain heap turned about(?),<note place="foot">Here the image is not clear. Is SHE suffering helplessly, as the corn turned in the process of winnowing (which she nevertheless does not seem to admit)?</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">applying foaming paste<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">poṅku tukaḷ āṭi</term>: here actually the wording is ambiguous (none of the words is familiar in this context). It might as well be still connected with the corn image: when the corn is thrashed, dust arises in the process.</note> to her night-like tresses</l>
<l rend="indent3">with a scent for bees to come, smelling of cool places<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">taṇṭalai</term>: or, lexicalized, of "flower-gardens".</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">that don’t bear nests in the broad-trunked Tāḻai trees.<note place="foot">What can be the relevance of line 1 for the rest of the poem? Is there any connection at all?</note></l>
<l>It is more cruel than the cord of tresses<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kūntal muraṟci</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a historical allusion to king <term xml:lang="ta">Naṉṉaṉ</term> who had made ropes from the hair of the womenfolk of his subdued enemies. (Is this the same <term xml:lang="ta">Naṉṉaṉ</term> who killed the girl that had eaten his mango in KT 292?)</note></l>
<l rend="indent">of Naṉṉaṉ with raised spear who drove away kings</l>
<l rend="indent2">with speedy good horses whose elegant broad manes glittered.</l>
<l>Will I ever forget your aptness in victory?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
